## 7 Separation of Ions

This section is concerned with how to separate ions in a given mixture of ions. Separation of ions is based on the different solubilities of compounds in different reagents. You will have to be familiar with the different reactions of cations and anions with the common reagents described in **Section 6**.

### Example (given a mixture of Zn\({}^{2+}\) and Cu\({}^{2+}\))

Zn\({}^{2+}\) reacts with NaOH to form Zn(OH)\({}_{2}\) (white ppt) which dissolves in excess NaOH to give a soluble complex Zn(OH)\({}_{4}\)- (colourless solution). On the other hand, Cu\({}^{2+}\) reacts with NaOH to form Cu(OH)\({}_{2}\) (pale blue ppt) which is insoluble in excess NaOH.

Since the two hydroxides formed dissolve in excess NaOH to different extent, by filtering the insoluble hydroxide, we can separate the ions from each other.

Recovery of the dissolved Zn\({}^{2+}\) ions can be effected by adding another reagent to re-precipitate the hydroxide.

