## 10 Heating

### Technique

* Close the air hole of the bunsen burner when lighting the flame. Once the flame is on, adjust the air hole to give a non-luminous flame. Normal heating is usually done with a bunsen flame in which the air hole of the burner is half opened.
* Get ready the materials needed to test for gas liberated before carrying out the heating.

When heating a solid,

* Use a clean and dry test tube / boiling tube.
* Hold the tube in an almost horizontal position.
* Apply heat gently initially (to remove any water of crystallisation present) and then strongly until no further change takes place.
* Be careful not to heat till the solid decomposes.
* Test for gas (if any) liberated. This would indicate the presence of a certain anion. The following sequence can be used:

1. use damp red and blue litmus papers. [to test for acidic gases or NH\({}_{3}\) (g)]

2. double gas through another test-tube containing limewater (aqueous calcium hydroxide) [to test for CO\({}_{2}\) (g)]

3. use glowing splint [to test for O\({}_{2}\) (g)]

